abstract: After two days of hearings with Mark Zuckerberg, the chief executive of Facebook, lawmakers in both parties said they favor regulatory action, but few thought it was imminent.
snippet: After two days of hearings with Mark Zuckerberg, the chief executive of Facebook, lawmakers in both parties said they favor regulatory action, but few thought it was imminent.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With bipartisan agreement, members of Congress said this week that Silicon Valley needed to be reined in with new regulations after Facebook’s chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, failed to allay concerns over the company’s mishandling of user privacy.

abstract: As Mark Zuckerberg, the company’s chief executive, prepares to testify before Congress, the company also said it supported the proposed Honest Ads Act.
snippet: As Mark Zuckerberg, the company’s chief executive, prepares to testify before Congress, the company also said it supported the proposed Honest Ads Act.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — For months, Facebook’s critics — ranging from Silicon Valley executives to Washington politicians — have been urging the company to do a better job of identifying who is buying political ads and creating pages about hot-button topics on its social media sites.

lead_paragraph: Even as it issues full-page apologies in print newspapers promising ritualistically “to do better,” Facebook and its allies have minimized the importance of the seismic revelation that the political consulting firm Cambridge Analytica, which worked on behalf of the Trump campaign in 2016, had gained access to the private information of about 50 million Facebook users.

headline_main: California Today: Facebook Under Fire, Yet Again
byline_original: By Pui-Wing Tam and Jose A. Del Real

abstract: The Federal Trade Commission is said to be examining whether the social media giant violated a 2011 agreement.
snippet: The Federal Trade Commission is said to be examining whether the social media giant violated a 2011 agreement.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal regulators and state prosecutors are opening investigations into Facebook. Politicians in the United States and Europe are calling for its chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, to testify before them. Investors have cut the value of the social networking giant by about $50 billion in the past two days.

headline_main: Facebook Faces Growing Pressure Over Data and Privacy Inquiries
headline_print_headline: Facebook’s Lucrative Formula Under Pressure From All Sides

abstract: As the social network’s list of woes grows, its 33-year-old founder, Mark Zuckerberg, will have to prove somehow he is not in way over his head.
snippet: As the social network’s list of woes grows, its 33-year-old founder, Mark Zuckerberg, will have to prove somehow he is not in way over his head.
lead_paragraph: For a business built on growing friendships, Facebook is making an astonishing number of enemies. Revelations that some 50 million of its user profiles were inappropriately harvested add to a list of outcries over the social network’s practices. It has come to the point where Facebook’s founder, Mark Zuckerberg, will have to prove somehow he is not in way over his head.

headline_main: Is It Time for More Adult Supervision at Facebook?

abstract: A political data firm tied to the Trump campaign gained access to information on 50 million Facebook users. Here is how it happened, and the uproar it has caused.
snippet: A political data firm tied to the Trump campaign gained access to information on 50 million Facebook users. Here is how it happened, and the uproar it has caused.
lead_paragraph: Our report that a political firm hired by the Trump campaign acquired access to private data on millions of Facebook users has sparked new questions about how the social media giant protects user information.
